{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639632"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17782"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17782"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72452"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10496"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57922"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10175"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24560"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72452"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENociceptors in the skin are specialised sensory receptors that detect potentially harmful stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the properties of cutaneous nociceptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myelinated nerve endings that respond only to temperature changes","Pacinian corpuscles that detect vibration","Encapsulated nerve endings that respond only to mechanical pressure","Free nerve endings that respond to tissue-damaging stimuli","Specialised receptors that detect light touch only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFree nerve endings that respond to tissue-damaging stimuli\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes cutaneous nociceptors. These receptors can detect mechanical, thermal, and chemical stimuli that could potentially damage tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyelinated nerve endings that respond only to temperature changes\u003C/strong\u003E - While some nociceptors have thin myelination, they respond to multiple types of stimuli rather than temperature alone.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPacinian corpuscles that detect vibration\u003C/strong\u003E - These are specialised mechanoreceptors responsible for detecting vibration and are not involved in pain sensation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEncapsulated nerve endings that respond only to mechanical pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Nociceptors exist as free nerve endings rather than being encapsulated, and they respond to multiple types of noxious stimuli.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecialised receptors that detect light touch only\u003C/strong\u003E - Light touch sensation is mediated by separate mechanoreceptors such as Meissner\u0027s corpuscles, not by nociceptors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENociceptors include two main types: thinly myelinated A-delta fibres that mediate fast, sharp pain, and unmyelinated C fibres that mediate slow, burning pain. Both types can respond to mechanical, thermal, and chemical stimuli that could cause tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cutaneous nociceptors are free nerve endings that respond to tissue-damaging stimuli including mechanical, thermal, and chemical signals.","A-delta nociceptors are thinly myelinated and mediate fast, sharp, well-localised pain.","C-fibre nociceptors are unmyelinated and mediate slow, burning, poorly-localised pain."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57922"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17782"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57922"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:49:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:50:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10496"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72452"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":